<H1><CENTER>Add Assignment Help</CENTER>
</H1>
<H3><HR SIZE="4"></H3>
Select the type of the assignment and enter its name (limit 15 characters).
For certain types of assignments, an initial file can be used to create
the assignment (not yet implemented).<BR>
Click on <STRONG>Add</STRONG> when done. 
<H4><CENTER>Assignment Types</CENTER>
</H4>
<UL>
  <LI><A HREF="edit_test.html"><STRONG>TEST</STRONG></A> - A test is a series
of multiple-choice, fill-in-the-blank and essay questions. The questions
can be randomly selected or random versions of tests can be administered.
When students submit their answers, the multiple-choice and fill-in-the-blank
questions are automatically graded. The instructor may then edit the student
answers to grade and comment on the essay questions. <BR>
<BR>
  <LI><STRONG><A HREF="forecast.html">FORECAST</A></STRONG> - A forecast
is a test which requests information about tomorrow's expected weather at
different sites in the U.S. Students may complete a forecast on a daily
basis. <BR>
<BR>
  <LI><STRONG><A HREF="inclass.html">INCLASS</A></STRONG> - An in-class
assignment provides the ability to record scores from tests or assignments
which are administered outside of ClassNet. Instructors can create inclass
assignments and enter scores for students. These scores will be reported
along with the other assignment types. <BR>
<BR>
  <LI><B><A HREF="edit_test.html">EVAL</A></B> - A student evaluation form
is a test with a due date. Students may enter and edit their answers until
the due date like a test. Instructors may view summary results after the
due date but cannot view individual student responses by student name. Essay
responses may be viewed by using the Data option to view the raw
data.<BR><BR>

  <LI><STRONG><A HREF="dialog.html">DIALOG</A></STRONG> - A dialog
assignment allows for private, ongoing, asynchronous conversations 
between instructors  and students. These conversations are stored by 
ClassNet and thus can be
analyzed and synthesized for research purposes at a later date. This 
assignment is ideal for students in areas such as teacher education and 
counselor education who wish to hold practice conversations with
secondary/elementary students/clients.<BR>
<BR>
</UL>
<P><CENTER><HR SIZE="4"></CENTER>
<P>Press <STRONG>Back</STRONG> in your browser to return to the Add Assignment
page.<BR>
</BODY>
